Here's how to implement all three pieces:

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage`

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- rest of your page -->
</ContentPage>
```

```csharp
// In your ViewModel
[RelayCommand]
async Task Back()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!discard) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

### 2. Guard the system back gesture / hardware back button

The custom `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the **toolbar** back button, but the user can also swipe back or press a hardware back key. Guard that in `AppShell`:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && args.Current.Location.ToString().Contains("editproduct"))
    {
        // Check if the current page's ViewModel has unsaved changes
        if (Shell.Current.CurrentPage?.BindingContext
                is EditProductViewModel vm && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard)
                args.Cancel();

            deferral.Complete();
        }
    }
}
```

### Key points

- **`GetDeferral()`** is required because the confirmation is async — without it Shell completes navigation before the dialog returns.
- **`args.Cancel()`** stops the navigation if the user picks "Stay".
- **`BackButtonBehavior.Command`** replaces the default back-arrow tap, so your ViewModel controls that path. The `OnNavigating` guard catches swipe-back and hardware back.
- Always **`await`** `GoToAsync("..")` — fire-and-forget causes race conditions.
